Influenza virus infections elicit lasting immunity rendering most individuals non-susceptible to viruses that circulated during their lifetime (
 Fonville et al., 2014). The virus population escapes collective human immunity by accumulating amino acid substitutions in its surface glycoproteins (
 Koel et al., 2013; 
 Wilson and Cox, 1990). Extensive genetic characterizations have shown that within each subtype many HA sequence variants co-circulate (
 Rambaut et al., 2008; 
 Fitch et al., 1997). These variants differ from each other by ∼10 substitutions and compete for susceptible hosts (
 Strelkowa and Lässig, 2012). The rapid sequence evolution results in a decay of immune cross-reactivity over ∼10 years (
 Smith et al., 2004; 
 Bedford et al., 2014; 
 Fonville et al., 2014; 
 Neher et al., 2016).
